text: A cadre of Brexit supporters have turned up to give the other side of the argument.
author: dp_williamson

text: Welsh Health Minister Vaughan Gething in the crowd at Parliament Square for the pro-referendum rally.
author: dp_williamson

text: What would Churchill make of today’s anti-Brexit march?
author: dp_williamson

text: Plaid leader Adam Price appears on the big screen at the Brexit march: “We can rebuild democracy.”
author: dp_williamson

text: PM says: "I have always wanted us to be able to leave on March 29". But she says as PM she could not consider a delay beyond June 30.
author: dp_williamson

text: Arch-Brexiteer Peter Bone tells PM: "If you continue to apply for an extension to Article 50 you will be betraying the British people. If you don't you will be honouring their instruction."
author: dp_williamson

text: PM: "We have a deal that keeps millions of livelihoods safe and secure... The deal is good for the country; it delivers Brexit and it should be supported."
author: dp_williamson

text: Corbyn: "All she is doing is running down the clock after a second heavy defeat." Says there has been a "concerted campaign" of bullying, blackmail and bribery.
author: dp_williamson

text: PM says British people "deserve better than this House has given them this far". Corbyn says talking of "indulgence" doesn't show much respect for democratic process.
author: dp_williamson

text: Theresa May says a long extension would mean "endless hours" and days of this House "contemplating its navel on Europe". "This House has indulged itself on Europe for too long".
author: dp_williamson

text: Jeremy Corbyn: "This is a national crisis." Challenges PM to discuss proposals. PM says it's a "bit rich" when he refused to meet her.
author: dp_williamson

text: Theresa May says she does not believe electing new MEPs "would be in anyone's interests".
author: dp_williamson
